The Cantharees Spanish flies used for
blisters) are very abundant in Sicily, and
that country furnishes great part of Eu-
rope. The Sicilians believe that they come
from Asia or Egypt, for they arrive regu-
larly every year in swarms, in the last days
of May and the first of June. The peasants
know by the odour which they shed, that
they are not far off, and after they have seen
them alight upon an olive tree, (this kind Of
tree particularly attracts them) they come
early in the morning and spread great
sheet under the tree; the tree is shaken and
all the flies fall upon the sheet They are
then put into earthen vessels and killed by
sprinkling them with vinegar from time te
time. They are afterwards dried, and
packed in tight boxes or casks.

This deserves to be noticed. Every year
on the fifteenth Of the first moon, which
generally correspondent to some day in the be
ginning of our March, the Emperor in per-
son goes through the ceremony of opening
the ground; he repairs In great state to the
field appointed for this ceremony. The
princes of the Imperial family, the presi-
dents of the five great tribunals, and an i'm
mense number of mandarins attend him.
Two sides of the field are lined with the Of
fcers of the Emperor's house; the third is
occupied by different mandarins; the fourth
is reserved for all the laborers Of the prov
ince. who repair thither to see the art hon
cred, and practiced by the head of the en-
pire. The emperor enters the field alone,
prostrates himself, and touches the ground
with his head in alteration OF lien, the God
of Heaven. He pronounces with a loud
voice prayer prcparedby the court of GER
emonies, in which he invokes the blessing
of the Great Being on his labor, and on that
of his whole people. Then, in the capacity
of chief priest of the empire, he sacrifices
an OK, in homage to heaven for all good
While the victim is offered on the altar, a
plough is brought to the emperor, to which
is yoked a pair of oxen, ornamented in a
most magnificent style. The prince laws
aside his imperial robes, lays hold of the
handle of the plough, with his right hand,
and opens several burrows in the direction of
north and south; then gives the plough into
the hands of the chief mantiarins, who, la
boring in succession, display their compar-
ative dexterity. The ceremony concludes
with distribution OF money, and pieces of
cloth as presents, to the laborers; the ablest
Of whom execute the rest of the work in
the presence of the emperor. After the
field has received all the necessary work and
manure, the emperor returns to commence
che sowing with similar ceremony, aud in
presence of the laborers. These cereno-
nies are performed on the same day by the
yiceroys Of all the provinces.

The horse is of all animals of Africa, the
1host valuable. This animal is said to be
found wild in the extensive deserts OIL the
north of Hadramant: this might have been
the case in ancient times, unless it should
be thought more probable, that the horse
OF Tartary has passed through Persia, and
has been only perfected in Arabia. The
horses here are distributed into two classes,
viz: the kadischi, or common Kind, whose
gcnealogy has not been preserved, and the
kociani, or noble horse, whose breed has
been ascertained fortwo thousand years,pro-
ceeding, as their fable asserts, from the stud
of Solomon. They arc reared by the Bedo-
uins, in the northern deserts between Basso-
ra, Merdin, and the frontiers of Syria; and
though they are neither large nor beautiful,
their race and hereditary qualities being the
only objects of estimation, the preservation
of their breed is carefully and authentically
witnessed; and the offspring ofa Kochain
stallion with an ignoole race, is reputed ka-
dischi. These will bear the greatest fa-
tigues and pass whole days without food,
living according TO the Arabian metaphor,
on air. They are said to rush on a foe with
impetuosity; and 1t is asserted that some of
them when wounded in battle, will with
draw to spot where their masters may be
secure, and if he fall, they will neigh for as
sstance; accordingly their value is derived
from their singular agility. and extreme do
cility, and an uncommon attachment to
their master. The Arabian steeds are some
times bought at excessive Rates by the Eng
lish at Mocha. The duke of Newcastle as
serts, that the Ordinary price OF an Arabian
horse is one, two, and even three thousand
pounds; and that the Arabs are as careful in
preserving the genealogy of their horses, as
princes in recording that of their families
the grooms are very,exact in registering the
names of the sires and dams of these ami
mails; and some of them are of very ancient
date in this species ofpedigree. Its affirm
ed that the Arabian colts are brought up
with camel's milk.

L. Gall, a German, has published a pam
phlct of 88 pages, to show the advantage of
making sugar from potatoes. He says every
farmer can make sugar in great or small
quantities, and render the importation of
foreign sugar unnecessary. Potatoes, he as
serts, are better than beets for sugar, one
hupered pounds of the former giving eleven
pounds of sugar, while the same quantity of
the latter gives only four pounds.

milk of the camel, grain being too scarce
and of too high price to be employed for
that use. The milk is given to these
animals sweet and sour, and this traveller
says he never saw horses in better condi

full articles.headline: CANl'HARIDEs.
full articles.article:
The Cantharees Spanish flies used for
blisters) are very abundant in Sicily, and
that country furnishes great part of Eu-
rope. The Sicilians believe that they come
from Asia or Egypt, for they arrive regu-
larly every year in swarms, in the last days
of May and the first of June. The peasants
know by the odour which they shed, that
they are not far off, and after they have seen
them alight upon an olive tree, (this kind Of
tree particularly attracts them) they come
early in the morning and spread great
sheet under the tree; the tree is shaken and
all the flies fall upon the sheet They are
then put into earthen vessels and killed by
sprinkling them with vinegar from time te
time. They are afterwards dried, and
packed in tight boxes or casks.

full articles.headline:
NATIONAL AGRICULTURAL FETE OF


TIE CHINESE.
full articles.article:
This deserves to be noticed. Every year
on the fifteenth Of the first moon, which
generally correspondent to some day in the be
ginning of our March, the Emperor in per-
son goes through the ceremony of opening
the ground; he repairs In great state to the
field appointed for this ceremony. The
princes of the Imperial family, the presi-
dents of the five great tribunals, and an i'm
mense number of mandarins attend him.
Two sides of the field are lined with the Of
fcers of the Emperor's house; the third is
occupied by different mandarins; the fourth
is reserved for all the laborers Of the prov
ince. who repair thither to see the art hon
cred, and practiced by the head of the en-
pire. The emperor enters the field alone,
prostrates himself, and touches the ground
with his head in alteration OF lien, the God
of Heaven. He pronounces with a loud
voice prayer prcparedby the court of GER
emonies, in which he invokes the blessing
of the Great Being on his labor, and on that
of his whole people. Then, in the capacity
of chief priest of the empire, he sacrifices
an OK, in homage to heaven for all good
While the victim is offered on the altar, a
plough is brought to the emperor, to which
is yoked a pair of oxen, ornamented in a
most magnificent style. The prince laws
aside his imperial robes, lays hold of the
handle of the plough, with his right hand,
and opens several burrows in the direction of
north and south; then gives the plough into
the hands of the chief mantiarins, who, la
boring in succession, display their compar-
ative dexterity. The ceremony concludes
with distribution OF money, and pieces of
cloth as presents, to the laborers; the ablest
Of whom execute the rest of the work in
the presence of the emperor. After the
field has received all the necessary work and
manure, the emperor returns to commence
che sowing with similar ceremony, aud in
presence of the laborers. These cereno-
nies are performed on the same day by the
yiceroys Of all the provinces.

THE FARMER.

ARABIAN HORSE.
full articles.article:
The horse is of all animals of Africa, the
1host valuable. This animal is said to be
found wild in the extensive deserts OIL the
north of Hadramant: this might have been
the case in ancient times, unless it should
be thought more probable, that the horse
OF Tartary has passed through Persia, and
has been only perfected in Arabia. The
horses here are distributed into two classes,
viz: the kadischi, or common Kind, whose
gcnealogy has not been preserved, and the
kociani, or noble horse, whose breed has
been ascertained fortwo thousand years,pro-
ceeding, as their fable asserts, from the stud
of Solomon. They arc reared by the Bedo-
uins, in the northern deserts between Basso-
ra, Merdin, and the frontiers of Syria; and
though they are neither large nor beautiful,
their race and hereditary qualities being the
only objects of estimation, the preservation
of their breed is carefully and authentically
witnessed; and the offspring ofa Kochain
stallion with an ignoole race, is reputed ka-
dischi. These will bear the greatest fa-
tigues and pass whole days without food,
living according TO the Arabian metaphor,
on air. They are said to rush on a foe with
impetuosity; and 1t is asserted that some of
them when wounded in battle, will with
draw to spot where their masters may be
secure, and if he fall, they will neigh for as
sstance; accordingly their value is derived
from their singular agility. and extreme do
cility, and an uncommon attachment to
their master. The Arabian steeds are some
times bought at excessive Rates by the Eng
lish at Mocha. The duke of Newcastle as
serts, that the Ordinary price OF an Arabian
horse is one, two, and even three thousand
pounds; and that the Arabs are as careful in
preserving the genealogy of their horses, as
princes in recording that of their families
the grooms are very,exact in registering the
names of the sires and dams of these ami
mails; and some of them are of very ancient
date in this species ofpedigree. Its affirm
ed that the Arabian colts are brought up
with camel's milk.

the majesty OF nature; the hoary summit OF
Mont Blanc, crowned with its eternal SHOWS.
No! vainly should ] seekto give you an idea
of this land of beauty All that is lovely,
romantic, glorious, and sublime in the works
of nature, are combined in these scenes OF
various enchantment Nothing can be more
animated than the scenery of Switzerland.
The whole country is overspread with ru-
raj habitations. Here you see the wealthy
substantial farmhouse, compactly built OF
wood, with its stern projecting roof. covered
with wooden shingles, secured with poles
and stones, unpaintrd, but well vanished
with its own native brown coat of exuded
rosin; perchance carved over with quaint
texts of scripture. and always sheltered un-
der venerable outrageous walnut trees,
from the fruits of which the peasant extract
their oil. Turn aside, and there, i'll deep
pastoral valley, at the base OF some beet
ling mountain, which seems to threaten its
humble roof with the terrific avalanche,
stands a sweet. lowly cottage, filled with bu-
sy inmates, and surrounded with every ap-
pearancc of rural labor and contentment.
High above, perched on some rrial summit,
accessible only to the shepherd and the
chamois, you behold the Alpine Chalet, or
mountain dairy, tenanted only in summer,
while the COW arc grazing Oh the fields.

full articles.headline: SUGAR FROM POTATOES.
full articles.article:
L. Gall, a German, has published a pam
phlct of 88 pages, to show the advantage of
making sugar from potatoes. He says every
farmer can make sugar in great or small
quantities, and render the importation of
foreign sugar unnecessary. Potatoes, he as
serts, are better than beets for sugar, one
hupered pounds of the former giving eleven
pounds of sugar, while the same quantity of
the latter gives only four pounds.

full articles.headline: HORSES FED WITH MILK.
full articles.article:
Major Denham relates that the Tibboos
in Central Africa, keep their horses on the
milk of the camel, grain being too scarce
and of too high price to be employed for
that use. The milk is given to these
animals sweet and sour, and this traveller
says he never saw horses in better condi
sien.

ia show his pupils the effect OF large doses of
nitre, in this complaint, as employed by the
Italian physicians. TO each OF the patients,
he gave half an ounce OF nitrc, dissolved in
a muciaginus mixture, to be taken IN the
course of the dav. In one patient, who had
been bringing up blood freely for four or five
days previously, and who had taken no other
medicine, the hemoptysis was completely
arrested during the first day at the hospital.
The dav after il returned, and was again
stopped by the same medicine, and did not
afterwards recur. This patient took tie
half ounce of nitre in the course of fonr
hours, and some dlsagrecable sensations

and the hemoptysis continued abundant-

man of Is years Of age, who had hcen sub
